Leger (as follows, “we” or “us”), as a market research company, often invites individuals to become research participants in major national research projects. Research participants may complete surveys to provide feedback and opinions on a range of social, political, lifestyle, marketing, and other questions, and may contribute other types of data. Through survey research, businesses, political organizations and governments learn from large representative samples of people. Opinions of survey participants help companies develop new products, make existing ones better, and improve customer service. Political organizations and governments also rely on survey research to advance laws and policies that the public wants or needs.
We respect the privacy of individuals who have been invited to participate in research that we conduct. For more than 25 years, Leger has been collecting information from consumers and citizens and, throughout that time, we have honored their privacy. 
Our Privacy Policy (“Privacy Policy”) discloses the Leger privacy practices for our survey respondents, panel members, market research study participants and market research consultants.  

The Personal Information We Collect
Personal Information means any information that can specifically identify respondent during a survey and/or enrollment process.  This information may include but is not limited to, first and last name, mailing address, phone number(s), e-mail address and in, certain circumstances, opinions and individual preferences. This information is used to contact respondents regarding market research opportunities, as well as to send incentive rewards. 
In most research surveys, we also collect demographic and professional information, some of which may be considered sensitive in nature, such as age, gender, occupation, income range, racial or ethnic origin, household composition, language preference, employment status, etc. We ask these questions to help ensure that the demographic profiles of individuals who kindly participate in our surveys accurately reflect the target population that we are trying to approximate.
We may also collect sensitive information that may include but is not limited to health-related information (disease, conditions and treatment) or financial information. We will never ask for sensitive Personal Information that could give rise to economic crimes if it were lost, misused or disclosed to an unauthorized party, such as credit card numbers, social insurance numbers, bank account information, passport numbers or driver’s licence numbers.

How We Collect Personal Information 
We will always collect respondent Personal Information by fair and lawful means. We collect Personal Information where we have obtained respondent consent to do so or as otherwise permitted by law.
We may collect Personal information directly from respondent or we may obtain Personal Information from clients or research firms who commission us to provide research services on their behalf.  We may also obtain Personal Information from list providers who have assured us that their lists comprise only individuals who have consented to be listed ("opt-in" lists). Finally, we may collect and use Personal Information obtained from publicly-available sources, such as telephone directories.
We may use a third party agent to host surveys or panel events to collect Personal Information, including email address. That information is delivered to Leger directly. Contractual agreements between Leger and third party vendors ensure that respondent Personal Information will not be shared with anyone and will not be used for any other purpose without their consent. 
Leger will give notice when Personal Information is collected or when any collected information is later to be provided to third parties. All notices will explain the need for the information and describe how the information will be used. Personal Information will not be used to directly market any products or services to identifiable persons unless that possibility has been disclosed in advance and the opportunity not to participate has been given.

How We Use Personal Information 
We identify the purposes for which we use respondent Personal Information at the time we collect such information from respondent and obtain his consent, in any case, prior to such use. 
We collect respondent Personal Information for the following purposes:
(a) to conduct quantitative or qualitative marketing and social research on behalf of our clients who include businesses, non-profit organizations and governmental institutions; 
(b) to understand respondent opinions to establish suitability for further quantitative and qualitative marketing and social research; 
(c) to meet legal and regulatory requirements.

In this context, we may use respondent Personal Information for any of the following reasons:
•	To invite a respondent to participate in survey research;
•	To conduct a survey research interview with a respondent;
•	To validate answers a respondent provided in a recent survey we conducted;
•	To manage our incentives programs and fulfill a respondent requests for such incentives.
•	To update and to ensure that our records of respondent Personal Information are correct;
•	To provide services and support that a respondent has requested;
•	To provide respondent with general information about Leger and our products and services;
•	To send a respondent important information regarding his participation, changes to our Legerweb panel terms, conditions;
•	To verify the integrity of submitted information;
•	To detect and to prevent violation of our Terms & Conditions;
•	As otherwise authorized by the respondent.
Data collected from market and social research studies is shared with our clients in aggregate (or group) form, and responses are not attributed to individuals, in other words we combine respondent survey responses with the responses of all other survey participants and report aggregate responses. Individual level responses are occasionally used, but never associated with any personal identifying information without the respondent explicit permission, except as otherwise stated herein.
